What should matter is the outcome, which is, for instance, how many exp-giving mobs can a class PRACTICALLY solo per hour. Theoretical arguments a-la &quot;the pet is like an extra party member, so if it does most of the work, it should take a share of the exp&quot; have no place when discussing exp penalties.<br>
<br>
The pet is not a party member, it's an ability integral to our class. Part of our offense and defense is built into the pet. That's why we don't have defense in the form of root, and that's why our nuke offense is weaker than a wizard's and even a druid's.<br>
<br>
The absurdity of the &quot;pet as party member&quot; argument can be seen even more clearly as follows. Instead of &quot;duoing&quot; with his pet, let the magician truly &quot;solo&quot; an exp-giving mob, without his pet. Let's take guesses on who will win, shall we!! It's clear that the pet cannot be seen as a party member, but as an integral part of the powers of the magician. Shamen and necros can solo without their pets, but magicians simply can't.<br>
<br>
Back to the point of how many mobs we can solo per hour vs other soloing classes.<br>
<br>
If we don't nuke, the fight lasts longer, we definitely get hit with the exp penalty, and the pet gets hurt. If we heal it to pull again quickly, we use a lot of mana, which leads to downtime. If we don't heal it and wait for the pet to regen, we have downtime. If we nuke to preserve pet health, we shorten the fight, but use up mana, which leads to downtime. The more we nuke, the bigger our chance of avoiding the exp penalty, but the longer the downtime that follows.<br>
<br>
WITH OR WITHOUT the exp penalty, there is no way of getting around the fact that a solo magician can apply his mana bar or his time investment to only one mob at a time (unlike wizards, druids, shamen), and there is no way of getting around the fact that our kills cause serious downtime (unlike necros, shamen, monks, rangers)<br>
<br>
Are magicians really twice as effective, when measured in 100% exp giving kills per hour, than wizards, druids, shamen, necros, monks and rangers? There's no way that this can be true.<br>
<br>
